          "text": "Small business websites need business name and logo prominently displayed, clear description of products/services offered, business hours and location with address, phone number and email easily accessible on every page, contact or quote request form, directions or map to physical location, photos of products/services/business interior, customer reviews and testimonials, links to social media profiles, menu or pricing information if applicable, special offers or promotions prominently displayed, and mobile-optimized design since most traffic is mobile. key: make it easy to find you, understand what you offer, and contact you. Everything should drive customer action - call, visit, or email. Your website is your 24/7 salesperson."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much should small businesses spend on their website?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For most small businesses starting out, spend as little as possible while maintaining professionalism. Mixo at $9/month creates excellent business websites with minimal cost. Durable at $15/month adds CRM features valuable for lead generation. As your business grows and website proves its worth through customer inquiries, upgrading to Squarespace ($23/mo) or Framer ($15-30/mo) makes sense for design quality and advanced features. Critical formula: if your website generates $500+ in annual revenue or saves 5+ hours monthly in time, spending $120-300/year (10-25% of value) is completely justified. Many small businesses overspend on fancy websites before proving business viability. Better approach: start with budget option ($9-15/mo), prove ROI through inquiries and sales, then upgrade if needed. Your limited budget goes farther on business growth and marketing than on expensive website technology."
        }
      },
